<!--Please SEE naming conventions at WP:MOSBIO, please do not add details like "Dr."(this includes adding postnominal degrees after name)-->'''James Wilson Holsinger, Jr.''', (born May 11, 1939 in [[Kansas City, Kansas]]) is an American [[physician]]. A former [[Major General (United States)|major general]] in the [[United States Army Reserve|U.S. Army Reserve]] (1962 to 1993), he has worked primarily in [[public health]] for over thirty years. He served as the [[Under Secretary of Veterans Affairs for Health]] from 1990 to 1993, during the administrations of [[George H. W. Bush]] and [[Bill Clinton]].<ref name="Veterans">{{cite web
|date=November 22, 1991
|url= http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=health&res=9D0CEFD71F3DF931A15752C1A967958260
|title= Investigator Cites Poor Care at Veterans Hospitals
|publisher= [[The New York Times]]
|accessdate=2007-07-19}}</ref> From 1994 to 2003, Holsinger was the [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of the [[University of Kentucky]]'s [[Chandler Medical Center]].   From 2003 to 2005 he served as [[Kentucky]]'s Secretary of Health and Family Services.<ref name="CV"/> 

On May 24, 2007, [[President of the United States|President]] [[George W. Bush]] nominated Holsinger to become the [[Surgeon General of the United States]].<ref name ="NYT071307"/> Holsinger's nomination became controversial and was never voted on by the Senate due to, according to his critics, anti-gay bias in his work in the United Methodist Church where he voted to expel a lesbian pastor and for a 1991 report where he characterized gay sex as unnatural and unhealthy.<ref name="010709AP">{{cite web
|date= January 7, 2009
|url= http://www.whas11.com/news/local/stories/090107whasasMedicalHoslinger.8fdeea.html
|title= Kentucky doctor appointed to President's Council on Physical Fitness
|publisher= [[The Associated Press]]
|accessdate= January 7, 2009
}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref name="LH010709">{{cite web
|date= January 7, 2009
|last= Vos
|first= Sarah
|url= http://www.kentucky.com/179/story/648677.html
|title= Holsinger named to fitness panel
|publisher= [[Lexington Herald]]
|accessdate= January 7, 2009
}}</ref><ref name="Banerjee June9"/> In January 2009, instead, Bush appointed Holsinger to fill a vacant unpaid position on the [[President's Council on Physical Fitness and Sports]] to expire May 2010.<ref name="010709AP"/><ref name="LH010709"/>

Holsinger obtained his medical degree in 1964 and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in [[anatomy]] in 1968, both from [[Duke University]]. {{As of|2009}}, he is a professor at the University of Kentucky. Holsinger is a leader in the [[United Methodist Church]], serving as treasurer of the [[World Methodist Council]] and was previously President of the Judicial Council.<ref name="CV"/>

==Early life and education==
[[File:Holsinger and Mother.jpg|thumb|right|Holsinger with mother]]Holsinger was born in [[Kansas City, Kansas]] to James W. Holsinger, Sr. (1906–1994), an Army [[Brigadier General (United States)|brigadier general]], and Ruth Reitz Holsinger (b.&nbsp;1909).<ref>{{cite web
|date=February 24, 1994
|url= http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/jwholsinger.htm
|title= James Wilson Holsinger, Brigadier General
|publisher= [[Arlington National Cemetery]]
|accessdate=2007-07-22}}</ref><ref name="resignation">{{cite web
|date=November 19, 2005
|url= http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LH&p_theme=lh&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&s_dispstring=Holsinger%20will%20be%20tough%20act%20to%20follow%20AND%20date(all)&p_field_advanced-0=&p_text_advanced-0=(Holsinger%20will%20be%20tough%20act%20to%20follow)&xcal_numdocs=20&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&xcal_useweights=no
|title= Holsinger will be tough act to follow
|publisher= [[Lexington Herald-Leader]]
|pages= A12}}</ref>

Holsinger graduated from [[Duke University]] with a [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]]  in 1964 and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in [[anatomy]] in 1968. He holds a degree from the [[University of Kentucky]] in human studies. Additionally, he holds [[master's degree]]s in hospital financial management from the [[University of South Carolina]], as well as [[biblical studies]] from the [[Asbury Theological Seminary]].<ref name="CV">{{cite web
|year=2006
|author= Holsinger, James W.
|url= http://www.ukcph.org/Portals/0/CVs/HSM/James%20Holsinger%20CV.pdf
|title= James W. Holsinger, Curriculum Vitae
|publisher= [[University of Kentucky]]
|accessdate=2007-07-22|format=PDF |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070929105319/http://www.ukcph.org/Portals/0/CVs/HSM/James+Holsinger+CV.pdf <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-09-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
|date=May 25, 2007
|author= Blanton, Jay
|url= http://news.uky.edu/news/display_article.php?artid=2325
|title= UK, State Officials Praise Nomination of James Holsinger
|publisher= [[University of Kentucky]] News
|accessdate=2007-07-22}}</ref>

He served as a surgical resident at [[Duke University Medical Center]] and [[Shands at the University of Florida|Shands Teaching Hospital]] where he was also a fellow in Cardiology.<ref name="CV"/> Holsinger has published four medical books and sixty-one [[peer review|peer-reviewed]] papers.<ref name="CV"/>

==Government career==
===Department of Veterans Affairs===
[[File:James W Holsinger official military portrait - 1993.jpg|thumb|left|Holsinger Major General Portrait]]Holsinger served for twenty-six years in the [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]] (VA) from 1969 to 1994.<ref>{{cite web
|date=May 25, 2007
|author= Gerth, Joseph
|url= http://www.courier-journal.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070525/NEWS01/705250431
|title= Bush taps Kentuckian as surgeon general
|publisher= [[Courier-Journal]]
|accessdate=2007-07-22}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> He served at five different hospitals, rising to become a Medical Center Director.<ref name="CV"/> In 1990, President George H. W. Bush appointed Holsinger as Chief Medical Director of the VA (title changed to [[Under Secretary of Veterans Affairs for Health]] in 1992).<ref name="Summary">{{cite web
|url= http://www.ukcph.org/Academics/HealthServicesManagement/HSMFacultyList/JamesHolsinger/tabid/599/Default.aspx
|title= James W. Holsinger
|publisher= [[University of Kentucky]]
|accessdate=2007-07-22 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070929105325/http://www.ukcph.org/Academics/HealthServicesManagement/HSMFacultyList/JamesHolsinger/tabid/599/Default.aspx <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-09-29}}</ref> He implemented the joint VA and [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] Contingency Hospital System, which could provide 25,000 beds within seventy-two hours for soldiers fighting in [[Kuwait]] during the first [[Gulf War|Iraq War]].<ref name="statement">{{cite web
|date=July 12, 2007
|author= Holsinger, James W.
|url= http://help.senate.gov/Hearings/2007_07_12/Holsinger.pdf
|title= Prepared Statement of James W. Holsinger Jr., MD.
|publisher= [[United States Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor, and Pensions]]
|accessdate=2007-07-22|format=PDF |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070725185621/http://help.senate.gov/Hearings/2007_07_12/Holsinger.pdf <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
|date=September 28, 2006
|author= 
|url= http://www1.va.gov/EMSHG/page.cfm?pg=61
|title= VA/DoD Contingency
|publisher= [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]]
|accessdate=2007-07-22}}</ref> He oversaw the nation's largest [[health care system]], which served one million in-patients and twenty million out-patient visits per year. Holsinger also developed [[health care]] policy for twenty-six million veterans.<ref>{{cite web
|url= http://www1.va.gov/health/gateway.html
|title= Veteran Health Administration - Programs & Organizations.  
|publisher= [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]]
|accessdate=2007-07-22}}</ref> 

When Holsinger assumed the post of Chief Medical Director, the VA was criticized for the quality of the care it provided. In 1991, Holsinger acknowledged that inadequate care had caused the deaths of six patients at its North Chicago hospital.<ref>{{cite web
|date=April 7, 1991
|url= http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=health&res=9D0CEFDE133DF934A35757C0A967958260
|title= U.S. Links 6 Deaths to Poor Hospital Care
|publisher= [[Associated Press]]
|accessdate=2007-07-22}}</ref> He commissioned a team to review the quality of care, and based on its findings suspended surgical care at the facility. Later, testimony before a [[United States Congress|Congressional]] subcommittee reported problems at more than thirty other veterans' hospitals.<ref name="Veterans"/> Holsinger responded, "Our patients are older, sicker and more complex than the average patient."<ref name="Veterans"/>

In 1993, he moved to Kentucky to become the Director of the VA Medical Center. He remained a consultant in cardiology for the hospital until 2003. Holsinger was awarded the [[Surgeon General's Medal]] by Surgeon General [[Antonia Novello]].<ref name="CV"/>

===United States Army Reserve===
Holsinger served for over thirty-one years in the [[United States Army Reserve]]. He was awarded the [[Distinguished Service Medal (Army)|Distinguished Service Medal]], the [[Legion of Merit]] and the [[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]] three times. He was assigned to the [[Joint Chiefs of Staff]] and promoted to [[Major General (United States)|major general]] in medical logistics working at [[the Pentagon]] under General [[Colin Powell]]. Holsinger retired from the United States Army Reserve in 1993.<ref name="CV"/>

==Academic career==
===University of Kentucky administration===
[[File:Gill Heart Institute University Kentucky 2007.jpg|thumb|right|Gill Heart Institute]]
From 1994 to 2003, Holsinger served as [[Chancellor]] of the [[University of Kentucky Medical Center]] with responsibility for five health colleges, four graduate centers, two hospitals and numerous clinics in Kentucky.<ref>{{cite web
|url= http://www.uky.edu/Regulations/Org/MedCente.pdf
|title= University of Kentucky Chancellor's Office. Organizational Charts
|publisher= [[University of Kentucky]]
|accessdate=2007-07-22|format=PDF}}</ref> Under Holsinger's leadership, the university built the [[Gill Heart Institute (University of Kentucky)|Gill Heart Institute]] and two research buildings, and Holsinger laid the groundwork for the expansion the hospital has undergone since he left.<ref name="statement"/><ref name="criticism surprises"/> Holsinger helped establish the Women's Health Center and the College of Public Health.<ref name="statement"/>  In 2004, Holsinger was named a Master in the [[American College of Physicians]].<ref>{{cite web
|month= March | year= 2004
|url= http://www.acponline.org/journals/news/march04/awards.htm
|title= College announces service awardees and new Masters
|publisher= ACP Observer
|accessdate=2007-07-22}}</ref>

In the late 1990s, Holsinger led an international team to address the [[AIDS]] epidemic in [[sub-Saharan Africa]]. Working with [[Africa University]] in [[Zimbabwe]], the team created a School of Health Sciences with nursing and public health programs to educate young people to deal with the AIDS crisis. Holsinger helped the university obtain a [[USAID]] grant to build the facility, which houses one of the few AIDS laboratories in southern Africa.<ref name="statement"/><ref>{{cite web
|url= http://www.gbhem.org/asp/viewNews.asp?id=241
|title= Africa University dedicates health sciences building 
|publisher= General Board of Higher education and ministry
|accessdate=2007-07-22}}</ref> In 2007, the program is preparing to field-test an [[HIV]] vaccine.<ref name="Testimony">{{cite web
|date=July 12, 2007
|url= http://help.senate.gov/Hearings/2007_07_12/2007_07_12.html
|title= Witness Testimony
|publisher= [[United States Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor, and Pensions]]
|accessdate=2007-07-22 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070712142932/http://help.senate.gov/Hearings/2007_07_12/2007_07_12.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-07-12}}</ref>

===University of Kentucky faculty===
After spending two years in Kentucky state government, he returned to the University of Kentucky as a professor for the graduate program in Public Health.  In 2011, Holsinger was inducted into University of Kentucky College of Public Health Hall of Fame for his service and dedication.<ref>{{cite web
|date= October 6, 2011
|author= 
|url= http://www.mc.uky.edu/publichealth/hallaffamepastinductees.html
|title= Hall of Fame Past Inductees
|publisher= [[University of Kentucky]]
|accessdate=2011-12-28}}</ref>

==Political career==
===Kentucky state government===
[[File:Frankfort Kentucky Capitol Building 2007.jpg|thumb|left|Capitol, Frankfort Kentucky]]Holsinger served as Secretary of the Cabinet for Health and Family Services for Kentucky under Governor [[Ernie Fletcher]].<ref name="criticism surprises">{{cite web
|date=June 10, 2007
|author= Vos, Sarah
|url= http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LH&p_theme=lh&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&s_dispstring=Criticism%20surprises%20Holsinger%20colleagues%20AND%20date(all)&p_field_advanced-0=&p_text_advanced-0=(Criticism%20surprises%20Holsinger%20colleagues)&xcal_numdocs=20&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&xcal_useweights=no
|title= Criticism surprises Holsinger colleagues
|publisher= [[Lexington Herald-Leader]]
|accessdate=2007-07-22}}</ref> He was responsible for the management of the state’s health and social services programs, including the five billion dollar Kentucky [[Medicaid]] program.<ref>{{cite web
|url= http://chfs.ky.gov/agencies/os/mission.htm
|title= CHFS Mission-Vision
