|accessdate=2007-07-22}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
|url= http://chfs.ky.gov/NR/rdonlyres/F4DE5941-6E93-40FE-B204-42B63A95DA80/0/CHFSExecutiveOrganizationalChart080806.pdf 
|title= CHFS Executive Organizational Chart
|publisher= Kentucky Cabinet for Health and Family Services
|accessdate=2007-07-22|format=PDF}}</ref> Holsinger also led the social services response to the 6,000 evacuees of [[Hurricane Katrina]] who relocated to Kentucky.<ref name="statement"/>

While serving as Secretary, Holsinger published a paper on physician professionalism stating that the autonomous practice of medicine contributes to physician dissatisfaction because of the prevalence of third-party payers and liability concerns. He recommended a new professional structure based on teamwork between physicians and "fair access to health care for all Americans."<ref>{{cite web
|year= 2006
|author= Holsinger, James W.
|url= http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/cgi-bin/fulltext/112467527/PDFSTART
|title= Physician Professionalism for a New Century
|publisher= Clinical Anatomy
|accessdate=2007-07-22}}</ref>

The ''[[Associated Press]]'' said Holsinger was a financial supporter of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]].<ref>{{cite web
|date=July 13, 2007
|author= Alonso-Zaldivar, Ricardo
|url= http://www.newsobserver.com/nation_world/story/635819.html
|title= Support is slow coming for surgeon general pick
|publisher= [[The Associated Press]]
|accessdate=2007-07-20}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> According to ''[[The Courier-Journal]]'', he contributed $23,000 over ten years to the party and its candidates, including President [[George W. Bush]].<ref name="CJ071007"/>

==Religious life==
===Good Samaritan Foundation===
[[File:Holsinger's Hope Springs Church 2007.jpg|thumb|right|Holsinger's current church]]
While Holsinger served as [[chair (official)|chair]] of the board of the Good Samaritan Foundation, a [[philanthropic]] [[health care]] organization, the [[United Methodist Church]] of Kentucky sued the foundation over control of $20 million in assets. Holsinger said the church was "only interested in the foundation's money, not its cause." In October, 2007, the case was decided in the church's favor.<ref>{{cite web
|date=October 17, 2007
|author= Green, Linda
|url= http://www.umc.org/site/apps/nl/content3.asp?c=lwL4KnN1LtH&b=2072519&ct=4535587
|title= Kentucky Conference wins lawsuit with foundation
|publisher= [[United Methodist Church]]}}</ref>

===Asbury Theological Seminary===
In November, 2007, the [[Asbury Theological Seminary]] [[board of trustees]] attempted to remove Holsinger from its board for a possible [[conflict of interest]] because he was also a board member of the [[Association of Theological Schools in the United States and Canada]], a division of which was investigating the [[Educational accreditation|accreditation]] status of the [[seminary]]. According to Holsinger, he subsequently resigned because he believed the board was asking him to be less than truthful with regulatory agencies.<ref>{{cite news
|date=2007-11-16
|title= Holsinger quits Asbury board
|publisher= [[The Associated Press]]
|accessdate=2007-11-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
|url=http://m.courier-journal.com/detail.jsp?key=155692&full=1
|date=2007-11-15
|author= Smith, Peter
|title= Holsinger quits Asbury board 
|publisher= [[The Courier-Journal]]
|accessdate=2008-03-26}}</ref>

==Nomination for Surgeon General==
===Confirmation process===
[[File:Holsinger and Koop.jpg|thumb|right|Holsinger with Surgeon General Koop 2007]]
On May 24, 2007, Holsinger was nominated by George W. Bush to become the 18th Surgeon General of the United States. The [[United States Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor, and Pensions|Committee on Health, Education, Labor, and Pensions]] (HELP) held the confirmation hearing on July 12, 2007.<ref name ="NYT071307">{{cite web
|date=July 13, 2007
|author= Harris, Gardiner
|url= http://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/13/washington/13surgeon.html
|title= Nominee for Surgeon General Testifies in Senate
|publisher= [[The New York Times]]
|accessdate=2007-07-19}}</ref>

Holsinger was supported by the [[American College of Physicians]] and former Surgeons General [[C. Everett Koop]] and [[Joycelyn Elders]]. He was opposed by several gay and lesbian organizations and the [[American Public Health Association]].<ref>{{cite web
|date=July 13, 2007
|author= Carroll, James
|url= http://www.courier-journal.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070713/NEWS01/707130447
|title= Surgeon general nominee vows science comes first
|publisher= [[The Courier-Journal]]
|accessdate=2007-07-19}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
|date=November 16, 2007
|author= Warren, Jim
|url= http://www.kentucky.com/181/story/232897.html
|title= Ex-surgeon general wonders: Is Holsinger’s confirmation ordeal worth it?
|publisher= [[Lexington Herald-Leader]]
|accessdate=2007-11-16}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> 

In October 2007, [[Scripps Howard News Service]] reported that the nomination was in trouble though he retained the support of several Republicans and the White House. The Senate committee was waiting for Holsinger to answer follow-up questions from the July confirmation hearing.<ref name="CincyPost Thompson">{{cite news
