The nomination was never voted on by the Senate and afterwards, in January 2009, Bush appointed him to fill a vacant unpaid position on the [[President's Council on Physical Fitness and Sports]] to expire May 2010.<ref name="010709AP"/><ref name="LH010709"/>

===Nomination controversy===
Following the nomination, Holsinger's views on homosexuality came under scrutiny, and several Democratic senators expressed concern or opposition to the nomination. In addition, individuals released statements supporting or opposing the nomination. Kevin Naff, editor of the [[LGBT]] newspaper, the ''[[Washington Blade]]'', charged that Holsinger has a "long record of anti-gay bias."<ref>{{cite web
|date=June 22, 2007
|author= Naff, Kevin
|url= http://www.washblade.com/2007/6-22/view/editorial/10821.cfm
|title= Dems should derail Holsinger  
|publisher= [[Washington Blade]]
|accessdate=2007-07-19 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070928014639/http://www.washblade.com/2007/6-22/view/editorial/10821.cfm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-09-28}}</ref> [[Paul Weyrich]], the conservative commentator, said opposition to Holsinger's nomination amounted to an assault on religious freedom.<ref>{{cite web
|date=June 27, 2007
|author= Weyrich, Paul
|url= http://www.renewamerica.us/columns/weyrich/070627
|title= A new (unconstitutional) religious test for a presidential appointee?
|publisher= [[Renew America]]
|accessdate=2007-07-19
|authorlink= Paul Weyrich}}</ref> Still others asserted that Holsinger is not hostile to homosexuals citing his support for a session on lesbian health issues at a health conference<ref name="criticism surprises"/> and the support of a former colleague who is a lesbian.<ref name = "Banerjee June9">{{cite web
|date=June 9, 2007
|author= Banerjee, Neela
|url= http://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/09/washington/09surgeon.html
|title= Surgeon General Nominee Is Assailed for Church Role 
|publisher= [[New York Times]]
|accessdate=2007-07-19}}</ref>

The critics were largely concerned with a 1991 [[white paper]]  he wrote titled ''[http://abcnews.go.com/images/Politics/Holsinger_on_Homosexuality.pdf Pathophysiology of Male Homosexuality]'' for a committee in the United Methodist Church reviewing its position that homosexuality violates Christian teaching.<ref name="Banerjee June9"/> According to [[Jake Tapper]] of [[ABC News]], the paper "purported" to discuss homosexuality from a medical standpoint.<ref name="Banerjee June9"/><ref name="ABCNEWS">{{cite web
|date=June 7, 2007
|author= Tapper,Jake
|url= http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/story?id=3251663&page=1
|title= Homosexuality Isn't Natural or Healthy
|publisher= [[ABC News]]
|accessdate=2007-07-19
|authorlink= Jake Tapper}}</ref> But the Rev. [[J. Philip Wogaman]], the main writer for the committee, said Holsinger imposed his views of homosexuality in the report.<ref name="Banerjee June9"/> According to Wogaman, Holsinger resigned after he anticipated that the committee was preparing to support the moral dignity of non-promiscuous homosexuality.<ref name="Banerjee June9"/> The church never adopted the committee's recommendations<ref>{{cite web
|date=July 12, 2007
|author= Tooley, Mark
|url= http://www.spectator.org/dsp_article.asp?art_id=11720
|title= Can a Methodist Be U.S. Surgeon General?
|publisher= [[The American Spectator]]
|accessdate=2007-07-21}}</ref> but continues to struggle with the issue.<ref>{{cite web
|year= 2004
|author= Task Force on Homosexuality and the Unity of the Church
|url= http://archives.umc.org/interior.asp?ptid=4&mid=6571
|title= Report of the Task Force on Homosexuality and the Unity of the Church
|publisher= [[United Methodist Church]] archives
|accessdate=2007-07-21}}</ref> 

Supporters of Holsinger's nomination defended the paper as a review of the relevant medical literature at that time.<ref name="Banerjee June9"/> Critics said the paper reflected a pre-1970s view of human sexuality, and that it had a political agenda and was not a scientific paper.<ref name="ABCNEWS"/> At his confirmation hearing, Holsinger said the paper did not represent his current views and was not “an example of my scientific work.”<ref name="NYT071307"/>

Critics have also expressed concerns about Holsinger's leadership of The United Methodist Church’s Judicial Council, the highest court of the Church. In 2005, the court defrocked [[Irene Elizabeth Stroud]], an openly lesbian minister, and in a separate case reinstated a pastor who had been suspended for refusing to allow a gay man to join his congregation.<ref name = "Banerjee June9"/><ref name="criticism surprises"/><ref name="NYT110105">{{cite web
|date=November 1, 2005
|author= Banerjee, Neela
|url= http://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/01/national/01methodists.html?scp=1&sq=Top+Methodist+Court+Backs+Conservatives+on+Gay+Issues&st=nyt
|title=  Top Methodist Court Backs Conservatives on Gay Issues
|publisher= [[New York Times]]
|accessdate=2008-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
|date=October 31, 2005
|author= Caldwell, Neill
|url= http://www.umc.org/site/c.gjJTJbMUIuE/b.1144999/k.E558/Church_court_reinstates_pastor_who_denied_membership_to_gay_man.htm
|title= Church court reinstates pastor who denied membership to gay man
|publisher= News Archives [[United Methodist Church]]
|accessdate=2007-07-19}}</ref>  However, a Judicial Council member said that the decisions should not be read as Holsinger's personal views because the council does not have the power to establish church law and lacked the discretion to rule otherwise.<ref name="criticism surprises"/> But, as the ''[[New York Times]]'' noted, "some council members opposed his views, and the bishops later rejected one decision."<ref name="NYT071007">{{cite web
|date=July 10, 2007
|url= http://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/10/opinion/10tue1.html
|title= A Nominee's Abnormal Views
|publisher= [[New York Times]]
|accessdate=2008-03-28}}</ref><ref name="UMC053006">{{cite web
|date=May 30, 2006
|author= Caldwell, Neill
|url= http://www.umc.org/site/c.gjJTJbMUIuE/b.1616949/k.D165/Bishops_president_foresees_more_dialogue_after_judicial_session.htm
|title= 
Bishops' president foresees more dialogue after judicial session
|publisher= News Archives of the United Methodist Church
|accessdate=2007-07-18}}</ref> On October 24, 2007, Holsinger announced he would not participate in the fall Judicial Council meeting set to decide on a case involving the appointment of a [[transgender]] clergy member,<ref>{{cite web
|date=October 24, 2007
|url= http://www.wfn.org/2007/10/msg00184.html
|title= Holsinger decides not to participate in top court's fall meeting
|publisher= [http://www.wfn.org/2007/10/msg00184.html]
|accessdate=2007-10-24}}</ref> which upheld the appointment.<ref>{{cite web
|date=October 30, 2007
|author= Locke, Michelle
|url= http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5g7U2BJ8HdNdUXQVCHBt60-tq15eAD8SJTPKO0
|title= Methodist Transgender Minister May Stay
|publisher= [[Associated Press]]
|accessdate=2007-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
|date=October 30, 2007
|author= Caldwell, Neill
|url= http://www.umc.org/site/apps/nl/content3.asp?c=lwL4KnN1LtH&b=1723955&ct=4565265
|title= Top court upholds transgender pastor’s appointment
|publisher= News Archives of the United Methodist Church.
|accessdate=2007-10-31}}</ref> Holsinger completed his 8 year term as a Judicial Council member and his 4 year term as its president in May 2008.<ref>{{cite web
|date= 2008-04-28
|url= http://www.wfn.org/2008/04/msg00257.html
|title= Five new members are elected to Judicial Council
|publisher= United Methodist News Service
|accessdate = 2008-04-29
}}</ref>

Finally, gay rights groups have expressed concerns that the church to which Holsinger belongs, Hope Springs United Methodist Church, had a program that tries to "cure" gays.<ref name = "Banerjee June9"/><ref>{{cite web
|date=June 1, 2007
|author= Jester, Art
|url= http://www.tugsa.net/Holsinger.html
|title= Holsinger's church role scrutinized
|publisher= [[Lexington Herald-Leader]]
|accessdate=2007-07-22}}</ref><ref name="FOX">{{cite web
|date=June 8, 2007
|url= http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,279032,00.html
|title= Bush Surgeon General Nominee Condemned By Gay Groups
|publisher= [[Fox News]]
|accessdate=2007-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
|date=May 31, 2007
|author= Roehr, Bob
|url= http://ebar.com/news/article.php?sec=news&article=1878
|title= Surgeon general pick concerns LGBT leaders
|publisher= [[Bay Area Reporter]]
|accessdate=2007-07-22}}</ref> However, the church's pastor denied this.<ref name = "Banerjee June9"/><ref name="FOX"/>

Supporters have pointed out that Holsinger faced down state legislators who, objecting to a session on lesbian health issues at a 2002 women's health conference, threatened to withhold funds.<ref name = "Banerjee June9"/><ref name="criticism surprises"/> A former co-worker who is lesbian wrote that although a "liberal Democrat", she strongly supported Holsinger as a leader with integrity.<ref name = "Banerjee June9"/>

===Public health stances===
====Smoking====
Holsinger has been a strong advocate for tobacco restrictions, implementing [[smoking bans]] in the entire [[Veterans Health Administration|VA]] hospital system<ref name="smoking ban">Condo, Adam. Smoking Ban Opposed for Veterans' Hospitals. The Kentucky Post. page 1K. January 16, 1992</ref> and pushing to increase the [[Excise tax in the United States|excise tax]] on cigarettes from 3 cents to 75 cents (ultimately raised to 30 cents) in a tobacco-growing state.<ref name="NYT071007"/><ref>{{cite web
|date=May 26, 2007
|url= http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LH&p_theme=lh&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&s_dispstring=Pick%20Him%20Holsinger%20good%20choice%20for%20surgeon%20general%20AND%20date(all)&p_field_advanced-0=&p_text_advanced-0=(Pick%20Him%20Holsinger%20good%20choice%20for%20surgeon%20general)&xcal_numdocs=20&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&xcal_useweights=no
|title= Pick him – Holsinger good choice for surgeon general
|publisher= [[Lexington Herald Leader]]
|accessdate=2007-07-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
|date=January 22, 2007
|author= Ward, Karla
|url= http://www.lcltfb.org/tobacco/tdn/TND-040122.html
|title= Poll Finds Support; Its Advocates In Legislature Hopeful
|publisher= [[Lexington Herald-Leader]]
|accessdate=2007-07-20 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070929020746/http://www.lcltfb.org/tobacco/tdn/TND-040122.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-09-29}}</ref> At his confirmation hearing, Holsinger said one of his top three priorities is “making America a tobacco-free nation”.<ref name="NYT071307"/>

====Childhood obesity====
Holsinger has consistently aired concerns about childhood obesity, pushing for a limit on [[junk food]] in schools, lobbying and educating for the promotion of exercise and improvements of school nutrition.<ref name="Obesity">{{cite web
|date=May 26, 2007
|author= Isaacs, Barbara
|url= http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LH&p_theme=lh&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_text_search-0=Holsinger%20AND%20familiar%20AND%20obesity%20AND%20issue&s_dispstring=Holsinger%20familiar%20with%20obesity%20issue%20AND%20date(last%20180%20days)&p_field_date-0=YMD_date&p_params_date-0=date:B,E&p_text_date-0=-180qzD&xcal_numdocs=20&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&xcal_useweights=no
|title= Holsinger familiar with obesity issue
|publisher= [[Lexington Herald-Leader]]
|pages= A1
|accessdate=2007-07-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
|date=May 31, 2007
|url= http://economist.com/world/na/displaystory.cfm?story_id=9256679
|title= Enter Dr Nice Guy
|publisher= [[The Economist]]
|accessdate=2007-07-22}}</ref> He included this as one of his highest priorities at his confirmation hearing.<ref name="NYT071307"/> He said he supported banning mass media advertising of junk food geared to children.<ref name="REUTERS071207"/>

====Readiness of Public Health Service Commissioned Corps====
During his confirmation hearings, Holsinger said that if confirmed he would focus on improving the ability of the [[Public Health Service Commissioned Corps]] to respond rapidly to emergencies.<ref name="NYT071307"/>

====Embryonic stem-cell research====
In 2002, Holsinger testified at a Kentucky legislative hearing discussing [[stem cell]] research. 
The [[Christian right]] characterized his testimony as supporting a "loosening [of] regulations". However, the White House said that Holsinger's concerns only involved the severity of the penalties.<ref>{{cite web
|date=July 9, 2007
|author= Ward, Jon
|url= http://washingtontimes.com/article/20070709/NATION/107090065/1001
|title= Bush nominee runs into crossfire
|publisher= [[The Washington Times]]
|accessdate=2007-07-19}}</ref> In 2005, he argued against a Kentucky anti-cloning bill, warning it could restrict future research. Holsinger testified that his father died of [[Parkinson's disease]] which is under investigation for [[gene therapy]].<ref name="CJ071007">{{cite web
|date=June 10, 2007
|author= Wolfson, Andrew
|url= http://www.courier-journal.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070610/NEWS01/706100522
|title= Holsinger assailed, defended over views on gays
|publisher= [[The Courier-Journal]]
|accessdate=2007-07-21}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> During the HELP hearing, Holsinger said he supported President [[George W. Bush|Bush’s]] stem cell policy,<ref name ="NYT071307"/> which restricts federal funding to already existing embryonic cell lines while providing funds for adult and animal stem cell research.<ref>{{cite web
|date=August 10, 2001
|author= Seelye, Katharine Q.
|url= http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=health&res=9D03E1DC123FF933A2575BC0A9679C8B63
|title=  The President's decision: the overview; Bush gives his backing for limited research on existing stem cells
|publisher= [[The New York Times]]
|accessdate=2007-07-20}}</ref>

====Sex education====
Holsinger said that [[Sexual abstinence|abstinence education]] is one way to prevent sexually transmitted diseases and unwanted teen pregnancy but also supported educating teenagers about condom use.<ref name="CQ">{{cite web
|date  =July 12, 2007
|author= Armstrong, Drew
|url= http://public.cq.com/docs/cqt/news110-000002549740.html
|title= Holsinger Tries to Convince Skeptics He Has Moved Beyond Controversial Paper
|publisher= [[Congressional Quarterly]]
|accessdate=2007-07-19}}</ref>

====Morning after pill====
Holsinger said he did not support restricting the availability of an emergency contraceptive known as the [[Emergency contraception|morning-after pill]], or [[Levonorgestrel|Plan B]].<ref name="CQ"/>

====Health insurance industry====
During the HELP hearing, Holsinger stated that he would seek ways to help the uninsured. "I think we need to have every American covered for health care."  He offered no opinion on how to achieve this goal.<ref name="NYT071307"/> He said that he supported banning drug companies from advertising on television.<ref name="REUTERS071207">{{cite web
|date=July 12, 2007
|author= Dunham, Will
|url= http://www.reuters.com/article/politicsNews/idUSN1139581620070712
|title= Bush surgeon general nominee denies he's anti-gay
|publisher= [[Reuters]]
|accessdate=2007-07-19}}</ref>

====Independence of the office of Surgeon General====
Two days before the HELP confirmation hearing, former Surgeon General [[Richard Carmona]] went public with claims that the Bush Administration censored his speeches and buried his scientific reports.<ref>{{cite web
|date=July 16, 2007
|author= Rovner, Julie
|url= http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=11854247
|title= Ex-Surgeon General Says Administration Interfered
|publisher= [[National Public Radio]]
|accessdate=2007-07-19}}</ref> When asked about this at the hearing, Holsinger said, “If I were faced with a situation that I felt I could not in good conscience do, I think I have a clear response to that. I would resign.”<ref name="NYT071307"/>

